name: Rental unit in Newark · ★4.59 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview: The historic Forest Hill Neighborhood of Newark, NJ, is the home of the world famous Cherry Blossom Festival.  It also boasts an impressive collection of colonial and Victorian houses. There is also the Grand Branch Brook Park that offers resident opportunities to residents to exercise or relax.  The neighborhood has easy access to public transportation. It is also convenient to Newark Liberty International Airport (-20 min. drive) and JFK Airport (1 hr. and 15 Minutes . Drive and 1 ½ hr. train.) Within walking distance there are Super Markets and various ethnic restaurants. Neighboring towns of Bloomfield, Clifton, Nutley and Montclair are within easy driving distance.
host_about: I am a man who wears many hats. I am an attorney, opera singer, landlord and investor. I love music, theater, ballet, animals and good food.  As a guest, I am always mindful of my host's needs. As a traveler, I have been to England, Scotland,  France, Italy, Hungary, Slovenia, Germany, Czech, and Slovakia. Budapest is my favorite city.  In addition of being fluent in Mandarin and English, I also speak some French, German and Italian

host_about:
Let me start by saying, thank you for considering our listings.

We are passionate about the guest experience. We stay in each listing from time to time so we can feel what our guests feel and make sure our guests have the best experience possible. Our company, BESTCITYROOM, com has its own website, IG @ BESTCITYROOM and (Hidden by Airbnb) page BESTCITYROOM where you can find more information about us and reach us for host consulting, Airbnb investments, monetizing Timeshares and doing Airbnb remotely worldwide.

We have been to many countries and endless cities. We have travel for over 20 years, fluent on 6 languages. There's a big probability we have been to where you come from and have gone where you going next, so feel free to ask for traveling advice.

Thank you for your business and keep traveling/exploring until its your time to rest.

name: Tiny home in Newark · ★4.79 · 2 beds · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview:
Hidden oasis of a Historical neighborhood, near park. Has lots of turn of the century charm with little bit of urban vibe. Ultimate commuters dream: Newark airport, train station, highways. Not far from Ironbound restaurants and pubs. Free on street PARKING, readily available.

NJIT, RUTGERTS, UMDNJ and major hospitals are accessible by bus or car.

You may borrow our bike to ride around the area, very scenic neighborhood. No house is alike.
host_about: We invite you to uncover the hidden side of Newark NJ and stay in one of our historic homes in Forest Hill and Ironbound. Both are truly the NJ best kept secrets - safety, friendly neighbors, 30 min to NYC, 20 mins to EWR. FH offers privacy and surburban feel, while Ironbound is a vibrant, "happening" place. We work in the city and communite to NYC daily, we're both new comers to this country and proximity to the Newark international airport remains very important to us. name: Rental unit in Newark · ★4.76 · 1 bedroom · 2 beds · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview:
This is a historic neighborhood, with the tree-lined streets and mansions of the old days. The famous Cherry Blossom Park (with the most cherry trees in the US), designed by Frederick Law Olmsted (who also designed NYC's Central Park), is a short walking distance away. It is equally beautiful at any season of the year.
The NJ Performing Art Center (NJPAC), with such events as Poetry Festivals and musical concerts for all tastes, and the Newark Public Library are a short ride away by the Light Rail.
host_about: We are a retired married couple who enjoys experiencing all the wonders of life -- especially traveling. To date, we've been to 4 continents, countless countries, and nearly every state in America. Among our favorite sites so far were the Great Wall of China, seeing the Northern Lights in Iceland, and Iguazu Falls in South America, to name a few. We also enjoy frequent visits to nearby New York City to see the opera, independent films, and all the other many cultural experiences the city has to offer.

name: Rental unit in Newark · ★4.96 · 6 bedrooms · 14 beds · 3 baths
neighborhood_overview:
It is very important to us that you understand our location before booking as that is the one thing we cannot change. We are in the Lower Broadway neighborhood just north of Downtown Newark which is home to a diverse population of Latinos and immigrants from other backgrounds. This means that great food, access to public transportation, shows and many other great perks are within walking distance.

This is a vibrant neighborhood that, like other key areas of Newark, is going through significant renewal and redevelopment, processes that are still very much under way (i.e., we are not as beautiful as we will soon be). If you don't let yourself be stopped by the couple of lots waiting redevelopment around us, you will find an array of small family-run restaurants and stores within 1-2 blocks radius of the apartment. Still, while luxury condos have begun to pop up here and there, we feel safe, and we think our neighbors are among the best, the Lower Broadway still remains much

My work and travel have taught me to appreciate people's hospitality and the warmth of their homes.  As a host, my husband and I will ensure your stay with us is nothing short of exceptional. As a guest, I will take really good care of your place and be sure to leave no trace behind! 

My husband, our lil' daughter Luna, and myself would love the chance to host you in our apartment in Newark!

We don't smoke or do drugs.

name: Townhouse in Newark · ★4.94 · 1 bedroom · 2 beds · 1.5 baths
neighborhood_overview:
Within a 15-min walk, you have access to:
TD Bank, Walgreens, CityPlex 12 (cinema), Value Zone (variety store), Dollar Tree, ShopRite (supermarket), post office

Nearby restaurants:
Applebee's, Wendy's, Chinese & Dominican cuisines, Dunkin' Donuts, Sonic, Popeyes, Taco Bell, McDonald's, Sarku Japan, Snap Back by Hook & Reel, Victoria Pizza, Vonda's Kitchen

Short bus ride or Uber/Lyft to downtown Newark & the Ironbound, where you'll find plenty of restaurants, shopping and entertainment (Whole Foods, Prudential Center, NJPAC, Newark Museum, Military Park, Harriet Tubman Square & more). Branch Brook Park, Weeqhuaic Park, Rutgers University, NJIT, Essex County College & Seton Hall Law School are also nearby.

Exxon gas station is 2 blocks away.

- Blaze Pizza
- Gateways to Newark : "Portraits" (largest mural on the East Coast)
- Treat Place

name: Home in Newark · ★4.65 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 2 shared baths
neighborhood_overview: Quiet street conveniently located 5 minutes from Newark Liberty International Airport. 10 minutes from Downtown Newark and Jersey Gardens Outlet Mall. 15-20 from other neighboring malls and stadiums (Short Hills, American Dream, Meadowlands arenas). We are also 30 mins from Lower Manhattan which is accessible by a direct bus that has a stop on the corner of Meeker and Elizabeth Avenue (down the street).
host_about: Hi, my name is  Patrick Mamudu. I am co-hosting this humble abode with my mother, Catherine Luke.  We have lived in the Southward section of Newark, NJ since the early '80s.  Our current interests are traveling, shopping, teaching (in various public high schools in the city of Newark, New Jersey), cooking, attending church every Sunday, Tuesday, and Wednesday, STEM (science, technology, engineering, and math), movies, music, and medicine.  Our ethnic origin is Nigeria, and we take pride in our culture. We love wearing our native culture clothes and also cooking many of the staple dishes from there (jollof rice, fried rice, moi moi, akara, suya, pounded yam, etc). A fun fact about Catherine is that she has been to several European countries during the '90s in order to sell many of the native clothing that is a staple in our country. I have been to London, Italy, Belgium, Switzerland, Germany, Spain, France, Austria,  etc.  We are devout Christians and believe that God is the centerpiece of our life; he has been good to us.  Our faith allows us to be hospitable hosts who value all of our guests. We take the extra step in making sure your stay is comfortable and feels just like home. We are also helpful in regards to movement within the Greater New York region.

name: Home in Newark · ★4.87 · 4 bedrooms · 4 beds · 2 baths
neighborhood_overview: Ironbound is a neighborhood in the city of Newark in Essex County, New Jersey, United States. It is a largely working-class, close-knit, multi-ethnic community covering approximately four square miles (10 km²). Historically, the area was called "Dutch Neck," "Down Neck," or simply "the Neck," due to the appearance of the curve of the Passaic River. The Ironbound is part of Newark's East Ward and is directly east of Newark Penn Station and Downtown Newark, and south and west of the river, over which passes the Jackson Street Bridge, connecting to Harrison and Kearny.

neighborhood_overview: Ironbound is a neighborhood in the city of Newark in Essex County, New Jersey, United States. Historically, the area was called "Dutch Neck," "Down Neck," or simply "the Neck," due to the appearance of the curve of the Passaic River. The Ironbound is part of Newark's East Ward and is directly east of Newark Penn Station and Downtown Newark, and south and west of the river, over which passes the Jackson Street Bridge, connecting to Harrison and Kearny.

name: Rental unit in Newark · 1 bedroom · 2 beds · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview:
Downtown Newark is a historic district consisting of early 20th-century towers. It contains the central business district and many art deco warehouses and offices that have been converted into residences. Newark offers a wide array of things to do.  There are parks, local and national restaurants, shopping, Museums, the Arts, Sports and a variety of other activities.

The Prudential Center, located in the heart of downtown, is home to the New Jersey Devils, other local sports teams and hosts many national concert tours. Also located in Downtown Newark are the New Jersey Museum of Art and the New Jersey Performing Arts Center.

From Craft Breweries to specialty local fare, Downtown Newark will not disappoint your hunger and thirst.

There are many events that take place on a year round basis that attracts locals and tourists alike.

If you run out of things to do in Newark, New York City is a 20 minute ride train ride away.

name: Home in Newark · ★4.89 · 3 bedrooms · 3 beds · 2 baths
neighborhood_overview: Ironbound is a neighborhood in the city of Newark in Essex County, New Jersey, United States. It is a largely working-class, close-knit, multi-ethnic community covering approximately four square miles (10 km²). Historically, the area was called "Dutch Neck," "Down Neck," or simply "the Neck," due to the appearance of the curve of the Passaic River. The Ironbound is part of Newark's East Ward and is directly east of Newark Penn Station and Downtown Newark, and south and west of the river, over which passes the Jackson Street Bridge, connecting to Harrison and Kearny.

neighborhood_overview: 07104 is prime area within Newark. Forest Hills is an uptick from Ditmas Park Brooklyn! Branch Brook park is actually the property line. Lots of bang for the dollar here without too much compromise. Enjoy!

Look no further...

If we please you, tell many friends...If we miss our goal, please tell me..
:)  :)  :)

 I love to make new friends, good food, to explore new places and have fun.    
Please contact me if you are planning to explore NYC, NJ,  or Costa Rica.
 
We will have a great time.... Once you are here...You are family!

If you fly into Newark Airport (EWR) and staying at least 7 days,  Book an UBER or Lyft taxi and send photo of bill for refund (Up to $10).

Thanks!!!

host_about:
Family first is our mantra. We love traveling and sharing our home with you.

Constantly searching for comfortable family friendly accommodations during our travels, has inspired us to provide the same for you. 

Our goal is to give you a home away from home with all the cozy comforts you are familiar with. Creating a space that is tastefully designed and curated but also giving you permission to live in it as you would at home. We believe that is the recipe that ultimately leads to a 5 star stay.

We know you will enjoy your stay with us!

Located west of the downtown area, University Heights is—true to its name—a partially residential hub of higher learning in Newark, New Jersey. Residents of this urban community enjoy convenient access to the wealth of shopping, dining and entertainment options available in Downtown Newark, as well as proximity to universities and colleges, including the New Jersey Institute of Technology, Essex County College, and a section of the Rutgers University Newark Campus

Go for a morning stroll or jog at Veterans Memorial Park. Visit the Feigenspan Mansion to see one of the last surviving examples of Second Renaissance Revival architecture in Newark. Set your sights to the stars with fascinating exhibits and dazzling celestial shows at Dreyfuss Planetarium. name: Rental unit in Newark · ★4.50 · 2 bedrooms · 2 beds · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview:
Downtown Newark is a historic district consisting of early 20th-century towers. It contains the central business district and many art deco warehouses and offices that have been converted into residences. Newark offers a wide array of things to do.  There are parks, local and national restaurants, shopping, Museums, the Arts, Sports and a variety of other activities.

The Prudential Center, located in the heart of downtown, is home to the New Jersey Devils, other local sports teams and hosts many national concert tours. Also located in Downtown Newark are the New Jersey Museum of Art and the New Jersey Performing Arts Center.

From Craft Breweries to specialty local fare, Downtown Newark will not disappoint your hunger and thirst.

There are many events that take place on a year round basis that attracts locals and tourists alike.

If you run out of things to do in Newark, New York City is a 20 minute ride train ride away.

neighborhood_overview:
Newark is the Garden State’s largest metropolis and is located just 8 short miles from Manhattan. Air, water, roadway, railway, bike path, footbridge and subway, Newark offers every manner of transportation imaginable, providing access that’s unbelievable.

The transportation in the Roseville neighborhood is super convenient! After taking the light rail to Newark Penn Station 2 blocks away, its only a 20 minute commute to Midtown, NYC by train.

For entertainment, the New Jersey Performing Arts Center (NJPAC). Take on the largest premium outlet mall in the state, The Outlet Collection, Jersey Gardens, welcoming over 18 million visitors a year. Other activities include the Newark Museum; NHL New Jersey Devils; and NCAA Seton Hall Men’s Basketball that you can watch close by at the Prudential Center.

name: Rental unit in Newark · ★4.89 · 2 bedrooms · 3 beds · 1 bath
neighborhood_overview:
This property sits just south of Downtown Newark. This area is very walkable and accessible to public transportation, making it easy to get around the city, within walking distance, a 13 minute walk from Prudential Center, 20-minute walk of New Jersey Performing Arts Center and 600 feet of Lincoln Park, where locals gather for events such as the popular Lincoln Park Music Festival, a community celebration of music, food, and culture that features live gospel, hip hop, and jazz. The New Jersey Institute of Technology, Newark Museum of Art, and Rutgers University Newark Campus sit nearby, so there are plenty of options for further education and entertainment around South Broad Street.

Popular points of interest near this accommodation is 10 min to Newark City Hall, Alumni Field and New Jersey Institute of Technology. The nearest airport is Newark Liberty International Airport, 2.5 miles and a 13-minute walk from Prudential Center.

neighborhood_overview:
Downtown Newark is a historic district consisting of early 20th-century towers. It contains the central business district and many art deco warehouses and offices that have been converted into residences. Newark offers a wide array of things to do.  There are parks, local and national restaurants, shopping, Museums, the Arts, Sports and a variety of other activities.

The Prudential Center, located in the heart of downtown, is home to the New Jersey Devils, other local sports teams and hosts many national concert tours. Also located in Downtown Newark are the New Jersey Museum of Art and the New Jersey Performing Arts Center.

From Craft Breweries to specialty local fare, Downtown Newark will not disappoint your hunger and thirst.

There are many events that take place on a year round basis that attracts locals and tourists alike.

If you run out of things to do in Newark, New York City is a 20 minute ride train ride away.

This property sits just south of Downtown Newark. This area is very walkable and accessible to public transportation, making it easy to get around the city; within walking distance, a 13-minute walk from Prudential Center, a 20-minute walk of New Jersey Performing Arts Center and 600 feet of Lincoln Park, where locals gather for events such as the popular Lincoln Park Music Festival, a community celebration of music, food, and culture that features live gospel, hip hop, and jazz. The New Jersey Institute of Technology, Newark Museum of Art, and Rutgers University Newark Campus sit nearby, so there are plenty of options for further education and entertainment around South Broad Street.

Popular points of interest near this accommodation is 10 min to Newark City Hall, Alumni Field, and New Jersey Institute of Technology. The nearest airport is Newark Liberty International Airport, 2.5 miles and a 13-minute walk from Prudential Center.

neighborhood_overview:
One of the premier cultural institutions in Newark is the Newark Museum of Art. It stands as one of the most comprehensive museums in the state, including a large collection of some 30,000 pieces of world-class Chinese, Japanese, Korean, Southeast Asian, Oceanic, and Tibetan art. The true star of the show is the Tibetan Buddhist altar – consecrated in 1990 by His Holiness the Fourteenth Dalai Lama himself. In addition, the museum boasts a planetarium, where you can explore the myths and legends of one of the most visible constellations in our night sky.
Another must-see destination in Newark is the Prudential Center. This state-of-the-art arena is home to the New Jersey Devils professional hockey team and also hosts a wide array of concerts and events – with big names such as John Mayer, Carrie Underwood, Jeff Dunham and many more!
Nature enthusiasts will delight in the stunning beauty of Branch Brook Park, the oldest county park in the United States, spanning a vast 360 acre

name: Home in Newark · 3 bedrooms · 4 beds · 2.5 baths
neighborhood_overview:
This is a quiet street a block away to all main bus lines on Bloomfield Ave. Branch Brook Park boasts the largest cherry blossom park in the country is two blocks away. Perfect for taking a stroll, bike ride or enjoying nature. It also has the super easy Light Rail tram (Bloomfield Av stop) that connects directly with major transportation hub of Newark Penn Station.
There is also a well stocked supermarket 2 blocks down.
It is a great space to rest and enjoy cozy evenings with family or friends.
You will be 15 min away from downtown Newark, 20 min from EWR airport, 40 min away from the city (either by car or public transportation).

name: Rental unit in Newark · ★5.0 · 1 bedroom · 1 bed · 1 shared bath
neighborhood_overview:
University Heights is a vibrant and diverse neighborhood located in the heart of Newark, New Jersey. As the name suggests, it is home to several major universities, including Rutgers University, New Jersey Institute of Technology, and Essex County College. The neighborhood has a lively atmosphere with many young students and professionals.

In addition to the universities, University Heights is also home to several museums, such as the Newark Museum, the New Jersey Historical Society, and the Institute of Jazz Studies. The neighborhood is also known for its beautiful parks, including Branch Brook Park, which boasts the largest collection of cherry blossom trees in the United States.

University Heights is a foodie's paradise, with a wide variety of restaurants serving cuisines from all over the world. From Mexican street food to Italian delicacies, there is something for everyone.

The neighborhood is well-connected with public transportation, making it ea
host_about:
Hello! 

I'm a proud New Yorker who has had the privilege of being shaped by the rich cultural tapestry that my heritage offers. My parents come from Egypt and the Dominican Republic, two countries with distinct cultures that have come together in a beautiful fusion.

Growing up in New York, I was exposed to a myriad of cultures, languages, and traditions. From the festivals and parades of the Caribbean and Latin America to the art and music of West Africa and South Asia, New York provided a glimpse into the world without ever leaving the city limits.

My Egyptian culture is deeply rooted in history, art, and religion. From the Pyramids of Giza to the cuisine with fragrant spices, herbs, and hearty dishes such as koshari, ful medames, and molokhia. Family is at the center of Egyptian culture, and gatherings are often filled with music, storytelling, and lively conversations.

The Dominican Republic, on the other hand, is known for its vibrant music, dance, and joyful celebrations. Merengue and bachata are a reflection of our spirit of rhythm and passion. The cuisine is a fusion of African, Spanish, and indigenous influences, with dishes such as mangu, sancocho, and chicharrón.

Growing up with these two rich cultures has given me a unique perspective on the world and a deep appreciation for diversity. I've been fortunate to experience the beauty of both Egyptian and Dominican cultures firsthand, from the traditional dances and music to the delicious cuisine and warm hospitality. These cultural influences, combined with the diversity of New York, have inspired me to explore other cultures and learn about their traditions and customs.

As I continue to travel and explore the world, I carry with me the richness and diversity of my heritage and the vibrancy of New York. I'm proud to share my cultural background with others, and I'm grateful for the opportunities that I've had to learn, grow, and connect with people from all over the world.

host_about:
Hello! 

I'm a proud New Yorker who has had the privilege of being shaped by the rich cultural tapestry that my heritage offers. My parents come from Egypt and the Dominican Republic, two countries with distinct cultures that have come together in a beautiful fusion.

Growing up in New York, I was exposed to a myriad of cultures, languages, and traditions. From the festivals and parades of the Caribbean and Latin America to the art and music of West Africa and South Asia, New York provided a glimpse into the world without ever leaving the city limits.

My Egyptian culture is deeply rooted in history, art, and religion. From the Pyramids of Giza to the cuisine with fragrant spices, herbs, and hearty dishes such as koshari, ful medames, and molokhia. Family is at the center of Egyptian culture, and gatherings are often filled with music, storytelling, and lively conversations.

The Dominican Republic, on the other hand, is known for its vibrant music, dance, and joyful celebrations. Merengue and bachata are a reflection of our spirit of rhythm and passion. The cuisine is a fusion of African, Spanish, and indigenous influences, with dishes such as mangu, sancocho, and chicharrón.

Growing up with these two rich cultures has given me a unique perspective on the world and a deep appreciation for diversity. I've been fortunate to experience the beauty of both Egyptian and Dominican cultures firsthand, from the traditional dances and music to the delicious cuisine and warm hospitality. These cultural influences, combined with the diversity of New York, have inspired me to explore other cultures and learn about their traditions and customs.

As I continue to travel and explore the world, I carry with me the richness and diversity of my heritage and the vibrancy of New York. I'm proud to share my cultural background with others, and I'm grateful for the opportunities that I've had to learn, grow, and connect with people from all over the world.

neighborhood_overview:
Newark is the Garden State’s largest metropolis and is located just 8 short miles from Manhattan. Air, water, roadway, railway, bike path, footbridge and subway, Newark offers every manner of transportation imaginable, providing access that’s unbelievable.

From Newark Penn Station, its only a 20 minute commute to Midtown, NYC by train.

For entertainment, the New Jersey Performing Arts Center (NJPAC). Take on the largest premium outlet mall in the state, The Outlet Collection, Jersey Gardens, welcoming over 18 million visitors a year. Other activities include the Newark Museum; NHL New Jersey Devils; and NCAA Seton Hall Men’s Basketball that you can watch close by at the Prudential Center.

1. Rutgers University Newark Campus: This is the heart of University Heights, housing various schools and departments of Rutgers University. It's a hub of academic and cultural activities.

2. Lincoln Park: To the west of University Heights, you'll find Lincoln Park, a large urban park offering green spaces, sports facilities, and a historic carousel.

3. Central Ward: University Heights is part of Newark's Central Ward, which encompasses a diverse range of neighborhoods, businesses, and community resources.

4. Fairmount: Located to the north, Fairmount is a residential area with local shops and schools.

neighborhood_overview:
Your Airbnb is located in Weequahic (pronounced Wee-QUAY-ic, or WEEK-wake "when spoken rapidly." Weequahic is a neighborhood in the city of Newark in Essex County, in the U.S. state of New Jersey. Part of the South Ward, it is separated from Clinton Hill by Hawthorne Avenue on the north, and bordered by the township of Irvington on the west, Newark Liberty International Airport and Dayton on the east, and Hillside Township and the city of Elizabeth on the south.

Part of the Weequahic neighborhood has been designated a historic district; major streets are Lyons Avenue, Bergen Street, and Chancellor Avenue.[2][3] Newark Beth Israel Medical Center is a major long-time institution in the neighborhood.

neighborhood_overview: Newark Ironbound is a culinary and cultural gem. Called the “Ironbound" after the large metalworking industry in the area from the early nineteenth century, the area has a distinct portugese and Brazilian culture from the wave of immigration from portugal in the 20th century and brazil in the past few decades. Some of the best barbecue and seafood restaurants can be found within walking distance from this apartment. My personal favorites are Sihana cafe and Mompou for casual fare - breakfast or lunch and fornos, sol de mar & Seabra’s marisquera for nice elaborate dinners.

Hi  This is Mario!    

Look no further... 
We have an excellent support team for great stays  and nice places! 
We add new things  weekly...

Also,  We provide excellent WiFi and 2 WIFI networks at each house.

You may want to try downloading ROKU app for use on our Roku smart TVs.

We use door codes.  No keys needs.
We change codes after each guest leaves.

I'm giving you $5 off each of your first 4 Uber rides. To accept, use code 'marioc2038ue' to sign up. Enjoy! Details:  uber site  and  invite  and marioc2038ue

I'm originally from Costa Rica.   My Grand parents moved from Jamaica to  Limon, Costa Rica to work on building a railroad  to San Jose 100 years ago.
Limon and Costa Rica are very friendly places.  So, is Irvington, NJ, USA.

We love to provide excellent service and to excel in everything we do.

If we please you, tell many friends...If we miss our goal, please tell me..
:)  :)  :)

 I love to make new friends, good food, to explore new places and have fun.    
Please contact me if you are planning to explore NYC, NJ,  or Costa Rica.
 
We will have a great time.... Once you are here...You are family!

If you fly into Newark Airport (EWR) and staying at least 7 days,  Book an UBER or Lyft taxi and send photo of bill for refund (Up to $10).   

Also, I love to ski ...Poconos Skiing resort is 50 minutes away.  You can learn  to Ski ,Snowboard, or just slide down the slopes here!!!

Thanks!!!
